cmCourseInfo.description: An examination of musical thought and practice in non-Western and Western traditions.
cmCourseInfo.title: Introduction to Music and Society
cmCourseInfo.exclusionsText: Does not count as an HMU elective.

cmCourseInfo.description: Western music from 1750 to the present.
cmCourseInfo.title: Historical Survey II
cmCourseInfo.exclusionsText: HMU226H1. Does not count as an HMU elective.

cmCourseInfo.title: Historical Survey I
cmCourseInfo.exclusionsText: Does not count as an HMU elective.

cmCourseInfo.description: An inquiry into the construction and reflection of gender and sexual identities in Western music. The course will emphasize discourses surrounding feminism and the role of women in music, masculinity studies, and gay, lesbian, bi-sexual and transgendered studies and their relationships to musical specific works, production and reception.
cmCourseInfo.title: Music, Gender and Sexuality

courses.name: Music under Totalitarianism: Mechanisms of Oppression,Modes of Resistance

cmCourseInfo.description: Oppressive regimes continue to constrain culture and freedom of expression. Taking an interdisciplinary approach, this course explores how totalitarianism has used music as an instrument of propaganda and control, and how musicians/activists have resisted. We will concentrate on Nazi Germany, the Soviet Union and the Middle East (especially Iran). The course covers Western art music but also other styles of music that have flourished under totalitarian regimes.
cmCourseInfo.title: Music under Totalitarianism: Mechanisms of Oppression, Modes of Resistance

cmCourseInfo.description: This course examines various roles of women in opera from Monteverdi to Berg. Topics including the power of the female voice, constructions of gender and identity, the diva or 'star singer' and images of women in society will be explored through DVD excerpts, source documents and selected readings.
cmCourseInfo.title: Women in Opera

cmCourseInfo.description: This class will survey some of the many music and dance traditions that can be seen and heard in a variety of Brazilian contexts. In addition to the most well-known of these, the carnival samba of Rio de Janeiro, we will explore lesser-known but equally vital practices such as samba de roda, forro, and axe music. Each will be studied in relation to sound, bodily movement, and pertinent social issues such as cultural politics, nationalism, racial identity, and tourism, among others.
cmCourseInfo.title: Music & Movement in Brazil

cmCourseInfo.description: Global Popular Musics is an introduction to popular music in its social and cultural context in a variety of international settings. Genres to be covered may include, but are not limited to, rock, hip-hop, country, and “world music”. The course will take an issues-based approach to the study of popular music, focusing on topics such as the interplay of tradition and modernity; media and technology; race, gender, sexuality, class, and other facets of identity; urbanization and migration; and the markets and legal structures surrounding music.
cmCourseInfo.title: Global Popular Musics

courses.name: Music, Sound, and Power in the Middle East

cmCourseInfo.description: Music and sound have long been considered to have spiritual and social powers in the Middle East. This survey introduces students to important musical genres, sonic practices, and influential practitioners from Egypt, Turkey, the Levant, and Iran and discusses their connections to fields of tradition, modernity, religion, gender, and politics.
cmCourseInfo.title: Music, Sound, and Power in the  Middle East

cmCourseInfo.description: Plainchant and polyphony, including topics for individual research.
cmCourseInfo.title: Topics: Medieval Music
cmCourseInfo.prerequisitesText: Completion of 4-course History requirement and one additional HMU elective, or P.I.

cmCourseInfo.description: Instrumental and vocal genres, including topics for individual research.
cmCourseInfo.title: Topics: Romantic Music
cmCourseInfo.prerequisitesText: Completion of 4-course History requirement and one additional HMU elective, or P.I.

cmCourseInfo.description: Developments and trends since 1910, including topics for individual research.
cmCourseInfo.title: Topics: 20th Century Music
cmCourseInfo.prerequisitesText: Completion of 4-course History requirement and one additional HMU elective, or P.I.

cmCourseInfo.description: The history of the discipline from its roots in Comparative Musicology in the 1880s to the modern, holistic study of music and society. Other topics include transcription, transmission, and cultural appropriation. A variety of the world's traditions are illustrated with audio-visual materials, and students contribute personal surveys, analyses and debates.
cmCourseInfo.title: Topics: Ethnomusicology
cmCourseInfo.prerequisitesText: Completion of 4-course History requirement and one additional HMU elective, or P.I.

cmCourseInfo.description: An intensive research project under the supervision of a faculty member. The project must be academically demanding and uniquely suitable for the individual student. Students propose a topic that is currently not covered in the curriculum or one that warrants further exploration related to research interests and/or musical goals. Available to students in 4th year on successful completion of the core HMU requirement plus at least 1.0 credit in HMU courses at the 300 level or higher, minimum cumulative GPA of 3.3 (B+), and availability of a full-time faculty advisor from the History & Culture division. Modes of assessment are determined through discussion between student and supervisor, but will usually include a public presentation of the research project.
cmCourseInfo.title: Independent Study
cmCourseInfo.prerequisitesText: In Year 4. Permission of the Division.
